The Limits of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear about how the world as we know it will come to an end, usually described as ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Club of Rome released its apocalyptic precursor, "The Limits to Growth," over forty years ago, its basic idea has been with us.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 "Limits to Growth" warned humanity that catastrophic collapse was imminent.
But since then, we have seen financial panic, but not any real shortages or production collapses.
Instead, resources created by human genius have more than adequately met human consumption.
But the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we are continuing a trend, preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues, while ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism declined, the Vietnam War became a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" sparked fear of pollution and ignited the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 title "The Population Bomb" made it clear.
In 1970, on the first Earth Day, people were pessimistic.
The intent of "The Limits to Growth" was to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people are consuming too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will eventually destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a level significantly poorer than today.
This view still resonates today, despite being completely wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, even though commodity prices have recently rebounded, overall they have fallen to one-third of their levels from 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dentistry materials, and thermometers, and by the year 2000, mercury consumption had declined by 98%, and prices had dropped by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally predicted to be exhausted by 1990 and 1992, respectively; today, their reserves are higher than in 1970, despite our greatly increased consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and halved the price.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries seeing an increase of 24 times.
"The Limits to Growth" was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth has slowed since the 1960s.
The food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being used, in addition to 2.7 billion hectares of reserves).
The rate of malnutrition has been reduced by more than half, from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has not stopped us.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where there was no air pollution from suspended particles, and people were happy farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys would make it impossible to breathe. Reality is completely the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people — equivalent to one in 500 — died from air pollution each year, most of it indoor air pollution.
Now, the rate has dropped to one death per 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that from malaria, its mortality rate is decreasing rather than increasing.
Nevertheless, the idea promoted by "The Limits to Growth" continues to influence the thinking of the public and elites.
Taking recycling, for example, it is often just a gesture that makes people feel better, costly and ineffective for the environment.
For instance, paper is usually sourced from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
The procedures related to paper recycling and government subsidies result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not actually threatened.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation have led to self-destructive policies, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization.
Furthermore, although pesticides and other pollutants are claimed to kill half of humanity, effective pesticide regulation results in only 20 deaths per year in the United States, while pesticide use has created a cheaper and more abundant food supply.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — the movement driven by pesticide panic — would add an extra $10 billion cost to the United States each year.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, and to maintain current output, 65 million hectares of farmland would need to be cultivated — half the area of modern-day California.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in fruit and vegetable consumption, causing serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer deaths each year).
Being obsessed with dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, while easily treatable diseases still cause 15 million deaths each year — equivalent to a quarter of total deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most of them can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing the global population of the poor by nearly a billion.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, lifespan, and quality of life.
The forty-year history since the release of "The Limits to Growth" shows that we need more, not less, growth.
Expansion of trade is estimated to bring over $100 trillion in benefits by the end of this century, far surpassing the benefits of the timid "comfortable" policies driven by fear-mongering.
But this requires abandoning the anti-growth mindset and using our limitless potential to create a brighter future.
